bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical Note
bioghist.p: Kenneth Charles Morton Sills (1879-1954) was Bowdoin's eighth president. A graduate in the class of 1901, he served first as Dean of the College (1910-1917) under William DeWitt Hyde. Following Hyde's death in 1917, he served as acting president until 1918 when he assumed the presidency. His tenure in office is the longest in Bowdoin's history, 35 years.

A number of important issues and events characterized his presidency. He served through three wars and the Great Depression, took steps to maintain Bowdoin as a small liberal arts college, fought for and achieved institutional control over athletics, ended the B.S. degree distinction and closed the Medical School of Maine, while strengthening other areas of the curriculum and the faculty.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Files of President Kenneth C.M. Sills include general office correspondence and specific correspondence relating to the closing of the Medical School of Maine, the conferring of honorary degrees, athletics, fraternities, the Institute of Modern Literature, the establishment of the Kent Island Station, the Tallman Foundation and the Committee on the Limitation of Numbers. The files also include correspondence with a number of prominent alumni including Percival Baxter '98, William W. Lawrence '98, Ripley Dana '01, Harvey D. Gibson '02, Clement Robinson '03, Robert Hale '10, and Robert P.T. Coffin '15. For related Kenneth C.M. Sills materials, see the Kenneth C.M. Sills Collection.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: This series contains annual reports of the President of Bowdoin College. From 1905 through 1976, these reports are part of the run of presidents' reports published as issues of the Bowdoin College Bulletin, and are shelved chronologically with the Bulletins. Content of the reports varies, but generally includes a review of the year, changes in faculty and curriculum, issues facing the College, and future needs of the College. A report from the Librarian is included in many of the issues, as is a report from the Dean of the College and the Director of the Museum of Art.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: This series contains baccalaureate addresses from June 16, 1918, to June 1, 1952, inclusive. Occasional addresses and statements made before various groups are also included. The bulk of addresses were made between 1918 and 1952. Included are chapel statements, memorials, opening addresses, and news releases. Some addresses are indexed. Contains both dated and undated files.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: Includes general office, personal and specific correspondence on subjects of ongoing importance to the college. Examples of such subjects include: alumni matters, athletics, faculty and curriculum matters, Committee on the Limitation of Numbers, the Carnegie Corporation, the Medical School, Kent Island and the Tallman Foundation, as well as various other external and internal committees.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: Series contains files of correspondence between President Sills and members of the Committee on Degrees regarding nominees for and recipients of honorary degrees. Also contains personal documentation by Sills of honorary degree recipients (photos, letters, etc.). Box 2 contains statistical information regarding profession, education, etc. of degree recipients from 1919-1938.

did.unittitle: President Sills Correspondence: Honorary Degrees 1939-1952;Summary of Honorary degrees, 1918-1946, Honorary Degrees, 1918-1946

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: This series contains fund records of the Sesquicentennial Fund of Bowdoin College. Includes correspondence among Sesquicentennial Fund committee members and correspondence to those who are donating money or have donated money in the past. Also included are some solicitations and progress reports on the growth of the fund.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: Correspondence is incoming and outgoing, often filed together. Filing can be by name of correspondent, by subject discussed, or by name of group involved. Activities represented include: administrative functions such as faculty affairs, curriculum issues, student academic and social affairs, communications with alumni, athletics, and external world affairs. Some correspondence parallels that found in subject files.

arrangement.head: Arrangement:
arrangement.p: Arranged chronologically, then alphabetically within each year.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: Printed ephemera includes pamphlets, programs and other printed material containing information written by or about Kenneth or Edith Sills. Also included is printed material from activities that the Sills attended or organizations of which they were members or officers. Printed ephemera continued to be collected after Sills' death and includes other material from memorial services and other programs honoring him.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: This series includes personal invitations, announcements, post cards, greeting cards, letters to and from Kenneth and Edith Sills as well as awards and biographical material. Invitations and announcements are mostly graduation and wedding invitations from 1932 to 1958. Letters, cards, and postcards are usually from friends or relatives, most are undated.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: Kenneth Sills' academic lecture notes are primarily notes from courses that he taught at Bowdoin in comparative literature and Latin. These notes include a set of 42 lectures, numerically arranged and a set chronologically arranged from 1935 to 1952. Much of the series is undated, but most lectures are from between 1930 and 1960. In addition, there are several folders of notes he took while he was a graduate student Harvard University. Most notes are manuscripts.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: This series primarily contains academic lecture notes that Sills took when he was a student at Bowdoin from 1897 to 1901. Most of the notes are undated. Also included are articles written by Sills that were printed in the Bowdoin Quill.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: This series includes budget item books from 1927 to 1954, and cash account books from 1906 to 1943. Sills' cash account books are lists recorded daily of items purchased and their prices. Budget items are notebooks that list Sills' private accounts of monthly expenditures, listed by categories such as insurance, groceries and entertainment. Also included is a folder of miscellaneous financial correspondence, records and receipts.

did.unittitle: Cash Account Books 1944-1954, Budget Items 1927-1954, and miscellaneous personal financial

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: Diaries are daily account books from 1891 to 1953. The books include Sills' records of travels, appointments and other daily activities and thoughts. Some diaries are more detailed than others with entries varying from several words to several pages. The series also includes his personal guest books, autograph books and book reviews.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: During World War II, President Sills and Dean Paul Nixon corresponded with Bowdoin graduates and undergraduates who were serving in the Armed Forces of the United States. This series primarily contains letters written to Sills and Nixon. Some copies of outgoing correspondence is also included.

scopecontent.head: Series Description:
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence between Sills and Bowdoin men fighting in the war. Also included are correspondence with Bowdoin parents regarding the location of their sons and letters from military organizations providing information for prospective soldiers.
